parse_expr

  - none

parse_binary_expr

  - lhs as true is passed to first ever invocation of parse_unary_expr

  - if this is ternary expression, then lhs is passed as-is to
    parse_expr's of ternary exprs (both forms)

parse_unary_expr

  - passed as is to parse_unary_expr, parse_operand and
    parse_atom_expr

parse_operand

  - openbrace allowed only for rhs

  - passed as-is to parse_expr on partial directive

    - it expects to receive compound literal, which is only possible
      with rhs

    - this means that partial directive is accepted only on rhs

  - passed as-is to parse_expr on bounds_check, no_bounds_check,
    type_assert, no_type_assert directives

    - it's a fluff anyway, these directives are valid only for some
      statements, so subsequent parse_check_for_statement will result
      in an error - parse_expr cannot result in a statement

parse_atom_expr

  - lhs is true only for the first iteration of the loop

  - openbrace is allowed only for rhs, where the operand is a literal
    type and expr_level is zero or more (so not a control statement)

    - the "not allowed in control statements" is about avoiding an
      ambiguity during parsing the, for example, if statements
      condition, where identifier followed by open brace could either
      be interpreted as identifier being a boolean variable and
      openbrace being a beginning of a block statement, or the
      identifier being a type name and openbrace being a beginning of
      a literal value of that type - so in control statements the
      latter is not allowed, unless we use a subexpression (so inside
      the parentheses), which increases the expr_level to >= 0

possible expressions:

  - lhs_expression (no literal value in operand, no literal value in first atom expression)

    - "no literal value in first atom expression" sounds pretty
      arbitrary, I would allow it because I don't think it introduces
      an ambiguity the literal value in operand would (ambiguous with
      block statement)

  - rhs_expression (literal value in operand, literal value in all atom expressions)

  - rhs_control_expression (literal value in operand, no literal value in any atom expressions)

another set:

  - expression_nlvo - no literal value in operand, literal values in atom expression allowed

    - this probably would be used in places where literal value in
      operand would normally introduce an ambiguity with a block
      statement (both begin with an open brace),

    - an lhs expression, basically

    - could have a "nie" variant ("no in expression") for for/switch
      control statements

    - binary expression will be expression_nlvo, op, expression

  - expression - literal value in operand allowed, literal values in atom expressions allowed

    - an rhs expression, basically

    - probably could be simplified to expression_nlvo + sole literal
      value

      - it could not - expression_nlvo could not expand to a binary expression of two expressions

    - binary expression will be expression, op, expression

  - expression_nlve - literal value in operand allowed, no literal values in in atom expression

    - this probably would be used in control statements of
      if/for/switch

    - an rhs expression in for/switch/if control statements

      - I think I'd use it for lhs expressions in control statements
        too, otherwise I'd need to introduce an expression that bans
        literal values altogether (expression_nlvo_nlve?)

    - binary expression will be expression_nlve, op, expression_nlve

    - could have a "nie" variant ("no in expression") for for/switch
      control statements

    - could this be simplified to some expression base + sole literal value?
